  (48,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'Tech is trendy when it comes to wedding registries','img/contents/4a5e1acce5e68c0a1c134ae150bb5b48.JPG','img/contents/98e78ea47726df622ed823b22e8855ae.JPG','Could they do it all over again, most couples married more than 20 years (75% of them) wish that they could have tech items on their registry. The most popular gift desires? A TV, camera or video camera, a tablet, smart thermostat and wireless sound system.',NULL,'<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Don&#39;t be surprised to see flat-screens instead of flatware on wedding registries.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">This wedding season, technology gifts are in style when it comes to gift-giving. Looking for a sign of the tech-influenced times? Regardless of how long they&#39;d been married, most couples (76%) say they would have preferred to register for an Ultra HD TV &ndash; a display that handles video that&#39;s four times the resolution of regular HDTVs &ndash; than a formal china place setting.</span></p>\n\n<p>More couples consider technology items appropriate for gift registries, according to a survey of brides and grooms commissioned by retailer&nbsp;Best Buy. Those married within the last five years were more likely to consider that OK (74% approved), but even 58% of couples who&#39;ve been married 20 years or more approved.</p>\n\n<p>&quot;Technology is of course ever present today and couples are really starting to include these tools in their weddings &ndash; including their gift registries,&quot; said Wendy Fritz, head of gifting registry for Best Buy, which began its own registry in February. &quot;It&#39;s no longer about a fancy china place setting, it&#39;s about a flat screen TV for a new home or a digital camera for the honeymoon.&quot;</p>\n\n<p>Could they do it all over again, most couples married more than 20 years (75% of them) wish that they could have tech items on their registry. The most popular gift desires? A TV, camera or video camera, a tablet, smart thermostat and wireless sound system.</p>\n\n<p>Most of those surveyed (74%) said they would prefer a useful gift such as a tech product over a sentimental gift. For Best Buy&#39;s survey,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.wakefieldresearch.com/\" style=\"color: rgb(25, 144, 229); text-decoration: none;\" title=\"http://www.wakefieldresearch.com/\">Wakefield Research</a>&nbsp;got input about wedding gifts from more than 1,000 brides and 1,000 grooms from May 29 to June 12, 2015. Half the respondents were married five years ago or less, the other half 20 years ago or more.</p>\n\n<p>In the four-plus months&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www-ssl.bestbuy.com/site/olstemplatemapper.jsp?id=pcat17000&amp;type=page&amp;eventtype=weddingregistrylist&amp;from=myaccount&amp;ref=30&amp;loc=NA&amp;ksid=c524f72c-2d47-482f-86be-4b7ce1c7a82b&amp;ksprof_id=402&amp;ksaffcode=17420&amp;ksdevice=c\" style=\"color: rgb(25, 144, 229); text-decoration: none;\" title=\"https://www-ssl.bestbuy.com/site/olstemplatemapper.jsp?id=pcat17000&amp;type=page&amp;eventtype=weddingregistrylist&amp;from=myaccount&amp;ref=30&amp;loc=NA&amp;ksid=c524f72c-2d47-482f-86be-4b7ce1c7a82b&amp;ksprof_id=402&amp;ksaffcode=17420&amp;ksdevice=c\">Best Buy&#39;s registry</a>&nbsp;has been available, the three most requested gifts have been the Ninja professional blender, Apple TV set-top box and Oster cordless wine opener. Other popular gifts that couples have registered for include&nbsp;Blu-ray Discplayers, streaming TV devices, wireless speakers, smart thermostats and small appliances such as hand blenders, slow cookers, griddles and irons.</p>\n\n<p>Best Buy is not alone in adding tech to registries. Other retailers such as Amazon and Target let you add TVs and video game systems, too.</p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-05 05:37:49',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (27,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'What is Apple Music and How Does It Work?','img/contents/98b6cdd9f7b259aad533306387ffe27a.png','img/contents/a62cc20b3887d3dc199e3d6d6d94e169.png','If you woke up today to find a new icon planted on the home screen of your iPhone, you might be wondering; what’s this new Apple Music app about, and what can I really do with it?','0','<p>If you woke up today to find a new icon planted on the home screen of your iPhone, you might be wondering; what&rsquo;s this new Apple Music app about, and what can I really do with it?</p>\n\n<h3><strong>Getting Started</strong></h3>\n\n<p>If there&rsquo;s one brownie point we can award to Apple Music straight off the line, it&rsquo;s that unlike Spotify (the only other real music streaming competition in its sights), you won&rsquo;t have to trawl the App Store to get the client installed.</p>\n\n<p>As soon as you upgrade your phone&rsquo;s firmware to iOS 8.4, Apple Music will automatically appear under the same icon that used to be reserved for local music that was stored on the phone&rsquo;s internal memory.&nbsp;(Of course if you don&rsquo;t want to use Apple Music, the fact that you can&rsquo;t remove the icon is probably a little annoying.)</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"imageedit_3_3121138114\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221432\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/500x409ximageedit_3_3121138114.gif.pagespeed.ic._MaF7lxlmW.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:409px; margin-left:-2px; width:500px\" /></p>\n\n<p>After the update is complete, you&rsquo;ll be launched into the Apple Music splash screen. The account tied to your phone will act as the default you&rsquo;ll use to register with the service, and all purchases (including your subscription), will be charged to the card you use in the iTunes App Store.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (1)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221384\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x534xFullSizeRender-1-623x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.aug2VR5PWm.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:534px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (4)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221381\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x540xFullSizeRender-4-616x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic._1q4fZDIoT.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:540px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Customizing the Experience</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Once the account is cleared you&rsquo;ll be taken to a screen that asks you which genres you&rsquo;re interested in the most. With the genre chosen, a cloud of various artists will pour in. If you don&rsquo;t see anything that pops out at you on the first page, you can tap the button in the bottom right to spawn more artist bubbles in the cloud.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (6)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221379\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x549xFullSizeRender-6-606x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.oj1auljP4l.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:549px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (5)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221380\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x563xFullSizeRender-5-591x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.0Et6EI_a0v.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:563px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /></p>\n\n<p>Once you find an artist you like, you can tap it once for &ldquo;like&rdquo;, or twice for &ldquo;love&rdquo;, after which the artist will blow up its size accordingly. If you see any that you could do without, just hold down your finger on their name for three seconds, after which they&rsquo;ll be deleted from the list.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (7)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221389\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x678xFullSizeRender-7-604x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.gHzjcG3jbz.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:678px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>Keep in mind that this is how Apple Music will start off by learning your preferences for everything &ndash; from what to play on the radio to what artists and albums are recommended during new release Tuesdays &ndash; so be as specific as you can to have the best possible chance of scoring a match in your general listening profile.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (14)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221393\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x572xFullSizeRender-14.jpg.pagespeed.ic.libh_PdV8M.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:572px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>In case your suggestions&nbsp;don&rsquo;t seem to fit later on, you can always go back in and reset the artist cloud by finding the option in your settings menu.</p>\n\n<h3><strong>User Interface and Overall Feel</strong></h3>\n\n<p>On its face, Apple Music doesn&rsquo;t stray too far from the aesthetic that the company first established with the design overhaul in iOS 8. Clean, matte lines are accented by Apple&rsquo;s trademark white glow, and just like the lock screen, the text of whichever album you&rsquo;re viewing will take on the colors of the cover art for that extra little dose of immersion.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (30)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221411\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x680xFullSizeRender-30-602x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.HL_2RrIrv_.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:680px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>As you might expect, all the buttons you need are here, and none feel out of place from where they ended up. Skip tracks using the arrows, check a playlist using the &ldquo;chart&rdquo; button, and share with the same icon you&rsquo;d use to upload a photo from your camera roll.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (11)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221385\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x673xFullSizeRender-11-608x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.O2G0CXQCEg.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:673px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>In the My Music tab, you&rsquo;ll see all the songs you&rsquo;ve saved from radio using the hearted &ldquo;favorite&rdquo; icon, along with any music that&rsquo;s already been stored locally on the device.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"imageedit_5_3276744794\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221436\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/410x698ximageedit_5_3276744794-601x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.z3JZc4pQLG.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:698px; margin-left:-2px; width:410px\" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Connect to Your Artists</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Connect is Apple&rsquo;s answer to Spotify&rsquo;s &ldquo;Follow&rdquo; feature, which gives users the opportunity to not only see when their favorite artists have released new music or tour dates, but also get an inside look at what they&rsquo;re listening to on their own accounts.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (10)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221386\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x550xFullSizeRender-10-605x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.SGPW6sfFeo.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:550px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (9)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221387\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x552xFullSizeRender-9-603x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.bWeGFM03I1.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:552px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /></p>\n\n<p>If we had to give it to either side, for now the advantage would sneak slightly over to Apple Music. Connect is an improvement on Follow in almost every way, faulted only for the fact that it&rsquo;s the first thing you&rsquo;ll see if click on an artist from search and they have it enabled (instead of their actual music).</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (27)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221402\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x677xFullSizeRender-27-605x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.GuD6InyS8w.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:677px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Radio and Available Music Library</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Both Spotify and Apple Music made the same deal with the record companies, and because neither are interested in stepping outside the bounds of copyright law, both have a nearly identical library of 30 million+ songs from all the same artists as the other. Apple has promised its service would feature exclusive albums from a select few artists such as Taylor Swift, though it&rsquo;s still too early to say whether there will actually be enough added content to justify the switch.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (31)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221410\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x479xFullSizeRender-31.jpg.pagespeed.ic.CP8CeTd9JC.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:479px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>Radio (found in the &ldquo;Radio&rdquo; tab mounted along the bottom navigation bar), works just as it has in Pandora and Spotify before it, using either pre-made genre stations or the &ldquo;Start Radio from this song&rdquo; feature to acutely customize your playlist</p>\n\n<p>.<img alt=\"\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221398\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x680xFullSizeRender-20-602x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.QblW_n-S9H.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:680px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>If you watched Apple&rsquo;s Music keynote earlier this month, you&rsquo;ll know the company has also debuted one major addition that&rsquo;s exclusive to its service alone: real, live radio. Instead of simply selecting a series of songs to listen to, Beats 1 Radio will feature actual DJs, in-studio interviews, and all the bonuses you&rsquo;d expect from a full-fledged radio station in your car. Combine this with NPR and ESPN Radio, and Apple&rsquo;s already&nbsp;got themselves a nice head start into the live market over their competition.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (19)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221399\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x415xFullSizeRender-19.jpg.pagespeed.ic.Gwm7lAow95.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:415px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /><img alt=\"imageedit_7_4394847884\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221437\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x294ximageedit_7_4394847884.jpg.pagespeed.ic.f_Hnbheh69.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:294px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Assorted Perks</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Aside from these choice picks&nbsp;though, most of what you&rsquo;ll find on Apple Music has already existed on Spotify for years now. Sections in Music like &ldquo;Staff Picks&rdquo; &ldquo;Mood Playlists&rdquo; &ldquo;Content Curators&rdquo; are all long-term staples of the Spotify brand, but Apple does the feature justice by making the music easy to sort through, and even easier to save to an outside playlist of your own design.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (28)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221413\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x673xFullSizeRender-28-608x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.xJjMvHwQWp.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:673px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>&ldquo;For You&rdquo; is essentially a glorified &ldquo;Discover&rdquo; panel in&nbsp;Spotify, and both feature a rich set of suggested playlists that are generated based on the artists you&rsquo;ve liked or listened to previously. Here you can listen to all kinds of music that you might not ever find on your own, some put together by real humans at the Apple Music team, while the rest is procedurally calculated the more often you use the app.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (15)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221392\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x544xFullSizeRender-15.jpg.pagespeed.ic.sVJ8Eogl7e.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:544px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<h3><strong>Subscription Pricing and Overall Value</strong></h3>\n\n<p>Apple knows they&rsquo;re late to the streaming game, and to make up for their lag in getting to the front of the pack, they&rsquo;re offering a free three&nbsp;month subscription to anyone who wants to sign up for the service.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (35)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221418\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/400x424xFullSizeRender-35.jpg.pagespeed.ic.2rCniCStua.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:424px; margin-left:-2px; width:400px\" /></p>\n\n<p>Spotify has responded in kind however, by giving new users the opportunity to sign up for three months of its own premium service for just $0.99 cents. The move is an obvious jab at Apple&rsquo;s plan, but either way you still end up getting a huge discount if you plan to keep the account active over the next year.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"imageedit_10_8343228049\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-221438\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/650x288ximageedit_10_8343228049-650x288.jpg.pagespeed.ic.pJzxktTfLV.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:288px; margin-left:-2px; width:650px\" /></p>\n\n<p>As far as user coverage is concerned, Apple is the clear winner with 100+ countries signed up and counting. Not all songs will be available in all regions, but considering that Spotify has only crested at about half as many markets (58), you should be sure to check the company&rsquo;s websites and TOS to verify whether or not you&rsquo;ll have listening privileges before dropping any debit cards on a month of service.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"imageedit_13_4697776582\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221439\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x552ximageedit_13_4697776582-603x1024.gif.pagespeed.ic.w1FVjgyn25.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:552px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (39)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221414\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/325x540xFullSizeRender-391-616x1024.jpg.pagespeed.ic.gotTfcRT-q.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:540px; margin-left:-2px; width:325px\" /></p>\n\n<p>Speaking of which; if at any time you decide you don&rsquo;t want to renew after your first three months are up, you can cancel your subscription by entering the Account tab (top right portrait). Select the &ldquo;Apple ID&rdquo; option, and in Account Settings you&rsquo;ll see the Manage option about three rows down.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"FullSizeRender (18)\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-221400\" src=\"http://cdn3.howtogeek.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/450x553xFullSizeRender-18.jpg.pagespeed.ic.rsVBPaaKdF.webp\" style=\"border:0px; height:553px; margin-left:-2px; width:450px\" /></p>\n\n<p>Flip the &ldquo;Automatic Renewal&rdquo; toggle from on to off, and your account won&rsquo;t be debited after the 90-day trial expires.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Apple Music may not be taking a revolutionary step in the world of online streaming services, but it still gives new subscribers&nbsp;enough fresh&nbsp;features and plentiful radio offerings to give the likes of Spotify and Tidal a run for their money.</p>\n\n<p>As with those services, for $9.99 you won&rsquo;t find a better deal to get all your favorite artists streamed straight to your phone from wherever you are in the world.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Source</strong></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.howtogeek.com/221356/what-is-apple-music-and-how-does-it-work/\">http://www.howtogeek.com/221356/what-is-apple-music-and-how-does-it-work/</a></p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-02 12:37:11',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (28,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'Wake up,  GEEK culture. Time to die!','img/contents/8933501bd0dde185d328c55e70e41e1e.jpg','img/contents/b1cc9f2ae9198868ff40e8f04d3cee4f.jpg','Looking back, we were American otakus, says comedian and author Patton Oswalt, who has a plan for reviving geek culture. \nPhoto: Chris Buck; styling: Jill Roth; prop styling: Nanci Bennet; grooming: Paul Castro/Aim Artists','0','<p><span style=\"font-family:brandon-text-wired,brandon-text,brandon-grotesque-1,brandon-grotesque-2,gill sans,helveticaneue-bold,helvetica neue bold,helvetica neue,helvetica,arial,lucida grande,sans-serif; font-size:20px\"><span style=\"font-family:ff-oxide-solid-web,helveticaneue-bold,helvetica neue bold,helvetica neue,helvetica,arial,lucida grande,sans-serif; font-size:14px\">I&rsquo;M NOT A&nbsp;</span>nerd.&nbsp;</span>I used to be one, back 30 years ago when nerd meant something. I entered the &rsquo;80s immersed, variously, in science fiction,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.ddo.com/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Dungeons &amp; Dragons</a>, and Stephen King. Except for the multiple-player aspect of D&amp;D, these pursuits were not &ldquo;passions from a common spring,&rdquo; to quote Poe.</p>\n\n<p>I can&rsquo;t say that I ever abided nerd stereotypes: I was never alone or felt outcast. I had a circle of friends who were similarly drawn to the exotica of pop culture (or, at least, what was considered pop culture at the time in northern Virginia)&mdash;Monty Python, post-punk music, comic books, slasher films, and videogames. We were a sizable clique. The terms&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">nerd</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">geek</span>&nbsp;were convenient shorthand used by other cliques to categorize us. But they were thin descriptors.</p>\n\n<p>In Japan, the word&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theotaku.com/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">otaku</a>&nbsp;refers to people who have obsessive, minute interests&mdash;especially stuff like anime or videogames. It comes from a term for &ldquo;someone else&rsquo;s house&rdquo;&mdash;otaku live in their own, enclosed worlds. Or, at least, their lives follow patterns that are well outside the norm. Looking back, we were American otakus. (Of course, now all America is otaku&mdash;which I&rsquo;m going to get into shortly. But in order to do so, we&rsquo;re going to hang out in the &rsquo;80s.)</p>\n\n<p>I was too young to drive or hold a job. I was never going to play sports, and girls were an uncrackable code. So, yeah&mdash;I had time to collect every&nbsp;<cite>Star Wars</cite>&nbsp;action figure, learn the Three Laws of Robotics, memorize Roy Batty&rsquo;s speech from the end of&nbsp;<cite>Blade Runner</cite>, and classify each monster&rsquo;s abilities and weaknesses in TSR Hobbies&rsquo;&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=products/dndcore/177550000\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Monster Manual</a></cite>. By 1987, my friends and I were waist-deep in the hot honey of adolescence. Money and cars and, hopefully, girls would follow, but not if we spent our free time learning the names of the bounty hunters&rsquo; ships in&nbsp;<cite>The Empire Strikes Back</cite>. So we each built our own otakuesque thought-palace, which we crammed with facts and nonsense&mdash;only now, the thought-palace was nicely appointed, decorated neatly, the information laid out on deep mahogany shelves or framed in gilt. What once set us apart, we hoped, would become a lovable quirk.</p>\n\n<p>Our respective nerdery took on various forms: One friend was the first to get his hands on early bootlegs of Asian action flicks by Tsui Hark and John Woo, and he never looked back. Another started reading William Gibson and peppered his conversations with cryptic (and alluring) references to &ldquo;cyberspace.&rdquo; I was ground zero for the &ldquo;new wave&rdquo; of mainstream superhero comics&mdash;which meant being right there for Alan Moore, Frank Miller, and Neil Gaiman. And like my music-obsessed pals, who passed around the cassette of Guns n&rsquo; Roses&rsquo;&nbsp;<cite>Live ?!*@ Like a Suicide</cite>&nbsp;and were thus prepared for the shock wave of&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://www.notquitegnr.com/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Appetite for Destruction</a></cite>, I&rsquo;d devoured Moore&rsquo;s run on&nbsp;<cite>Swamp Thing</cite>&nbsp;and thus eased nicely into his&nbsp;<cite>Watchmen</cite>. I&rsquo;d also read the individual issues of Miller&rsquo;s&nbsp;<cite>Daredevil: Born Again</cite>&nbsp;run, so when&nbsp;<cite>The Dark Knight Returns</cite>&nbsp;was reviewed by&nbsp;<cite>The New York Times</cite>, I could say I saw it coming. And I&rsquo;d consumed so many single-issue guest-writing stints of Gaiman&rsquo;s that when he was finally given&nbsp;<cite>The Sandman</cite>&nbsp;title all to himself, I was first in line and knew the language.</p>\n\n<p>Admittedly, there&rsquo;s a chilly thrill in moving with the herd while quietly being tuned in to something dark, complicated, and unknown just beneath the topsoil of popularity. Something about which, while we moved&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">with</span>the herd, we could share a wink and a nod with two or three other similarly connected herdlings.</p>\n\n<p>When our coworkers nodded along to Springsteen and Madonna songs at the local Bennigan&rsquo;s, my select friends and I would quietly trade out-of-context lines from&nbsp;<cite>Monty Python</cite>&nbsp;sketches&mdash;a thieves&rsquo; cant, a code language used for identification. We needed it, too, because the essence of our culture&mdash;our &ldquo;escape hatch&rdquo; culture&mdash;would begin to change in 1987.</p>\n\n<p>That was the year the final issue of&nbsp;<cite>Watchmen</cite>&nbsp;came out, in October. After that, it seemed like everything that was part of my otaku world was out in the open and up for grabs, if only out of context. I wasn&rsquo;t seeing the hard line between &ldquo;nerds&rdquo; and &ldquo;normals&rdquo; anymore. It was the last year that a T-shirt or music preference or pastime (Dungeons &amp; Dragons had long since lost its dangerous, Satanic, suicide-inducing street cred) could set you apart from the surface dwellers. Pretty soon, being the only person who was into something didn&rsquo;t make you outcast; it made you ahead of the curve and someone people were quicker to befriend than shun. Ironically, surface dwellers began repurposing the symbols and phrases and tokens of the erstwhile outcast underground.</p>\n\n<p>Fast-forward to now:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/bobafett/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Boba Fett&rsquo;s</a>&nbsp;helmet emblazoned on sleeveless T-shirts worn by gym douches hefting dumbbells. The&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/10/26/glee-rocky-horror-episode-recap/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Glee</a></cite>&nbsp;kids performing the songs from&nbsp;<cite>The Rocky Horror Picture Show</cite>. And Toad the Wet Sprocket, a band that took its name from a&nbsp;<cite>Monty Python</cite>&nbsp;riff, joining the permanent soundtrack of a night out at Bennigan&rsquo;s. Our below-the-topsoil passions have been rudely dug up and displayed in the noonday sun.&nbsp;<cite>The Lord of the Rings</cite>&nbsp;used to be ours and<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">only ours</span>&nbsp;simply because of the sheer goddamn thickness of the books. Twenty years later, the entire cast and crew would be trooping onstage at the Oscars to collect their statuettes, and replicas of the One Ring would be sold as bling.</p>\n\n<p>The topsoil has been scraped away, forever, in 2010. In fact, it&rsquo;s been dug up, thrown into the air, and allowed to rain down and coat everyone in a thin gray-brown mist called the Internet. Everyone considers themselves otaku about something&mdash;whether it&rsquo;s the mythology of&nbsp;<cite>Lost</cite>&nbsp;or the minor intrigues of&nbsp;<cite>Top Chef</cite>.&nbsp;<cite>American Idol</cite>&nbsp;inspires&mdash;if not in depth, at least in length and passion&mdash;the same number of conversations as does&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://www.hbo.com/the-wire/index.html\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">The Wire</a></cite>. There are no more hidden thought-palaces&mdash;they&rsquo;re easily accessed websites, or Facebook pages with thousands of fans. And I&rsquo;m not going to bore you with the step-by-step specifics of how it happened. In the timeline of the upheaval, part of the graph should be interrupted by the words the Internet. And now here we are.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"Photo: Chris Buck\" class=\"cursor-zoom\" src=\"http://www.wired.com/magazine/wp-content/images/19-01/ff_angrynerd_geekculture2_f.jpg\" style=\"border:0px; box-sizing:border-box; cursor:zoom-in; display:block; float:left; font-family:inherit; font-style:inherit; font-weight:inherit; margin:0px 5px; max-width:100%; outline:0px; padding:0px; vertical-align:baseline; width:532px\" title=\"Geek Culture Is Dead, But It Can Be Revived\" /></p>\n\n<p>Before we can start to rebuild geek culture, we first have to destroy it.&nbsp;<br />\nPhoto: Chris Buck; styling: Jill Roth; prop styling: Nanci Bennet; grooming: Paul Castro/Aim Artists</p>\n\n<p>The problem with the Internet, however, is that it lets anyone become otaku about anything&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">instantly</span>. In the &rsquo;80s, you couldn&rsquo;t get up to speed on an entire genre in a weekend. You had to wait, month to month, for the issues of<cite><a href=\"http://watchmenmovie.warnerbros.com/dvd/index.html\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Watchmen</a></cite>&nbsp;to come out. We couldn&rsquo;t BitTorrent the latest John Woo film or digitally download an entire decade&rsquo;s worth of grunge or hip hop. Hell, there were a few weeks during the spring of 1991 when we couldn&rsquo;t tell whether Nirvana or Tad would be the next band to break big. Imagine the terror!</p>\n\n<p>But then reflect on the advantages. Waiting for the next issue, movie, or album gave you time to reread, rewatch, reabsorb whatever you loved, so you brought your own idiosyncratic love of that thing to your thought-palace. People who were obsessed with&nbsp;<cite>Star Trek</cite>&nbsp;or the&nbsp;<cite>Ender&rsquo;s Game</cite>&nbsp;books were all obsessed with the same object, but its light shone differently on each person. Everyone had to create in their mind unanswered questions or what-ifs. What if Leia, not Luke, had become a Jedi? What happens after Rorschach&rsquo;s journal is found at the end of&nbsp;<cite>Watchmen</cite>? What the hell was&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://www.amctv.com/originals/the-prisoner/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">The Prisoner</a></cite>&nbsp;about?</p>\n\n<p>None of that&rsquo;s necessary anymore. When everyone has easy access to their favorite diversions and every diversion comes with a rabbit hole&rsquo;s worth of extra features and deleted scenes and hidden hacks to tumble down and never emerge from, then we&rsquo;re all just adding to an ever-swelling, soon-to-erupt volcano of trivia, re-contextualized and forever rebooted. We&rsquo;re on the brink of Etewaf: Everything That Ever Was&mdash;Available Forever.</p>\n\n<p>I know it sounds great, but there&rsquo;s a danger: Everything we have today that&rsquo;s cool comes from someone wanting more of something they loved in the past. Action figures, videogames, superhero movies, iPods: All are continuations of a love that wanted more. Ever see action figures from the &rsquo;70s, each with that same generic Anson Williams body and one-piece costume with the big clumsy snap on the back? Or played&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adventure_%28Atari_2600%29\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Atari&rsquo;s&nbsp;<cite>Adventure</cite></a>, found the secret room, and thought, that&rsquo;s it? Can we all admit the final battle in<cite>Superman II</cite>&nbsp;looks like a local commercial for a personal-injury attorney? And how many people had their cassette of the&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repo_Man_(film)\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Repo Man</a></cite>&nbsp;soundtrack eaten by a Walkman?</p>\n\n<p>Now, with everyone more or less otaku and everything<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">immediately</span>&nbsp;awesome (or, if not, just as immediately rebooted or recut as a hilarious YouTube or Funny or Die spoof), the old inner longing for more or better that made our present pop culture so amazing is dwindling.&nbsp;<cite>The Onion</cite>&lsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.avclub.com/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">A.V. Club</a>&mdash;essential and transcendent in so many ways&mdash;has a weekly feature called&nbsp;<cite>Gateways to Geekery</cite>, in which an entire artistic subculture&mdash;say, anime, H. P. Lovecraft, or the Marx Brothers&mdash;is mapped out so you can become otaku on it but avoid its more tedious aspects.</p>\n\n<p>Here&rsquo;s the danger: That creates weak otakus. Etewaf doesn&rsquo;t produce a new generation of artists&mdash;just an army of sated consumers. Why create anything new when there&rsquo;s a mountain of freshly excavated pop culture to recut, repurpose, and manipulate on your iMovie?&nbsp;<cite>The Shining</cite>&nbsp;can be remade into a comedy trailer. Both movie versions of the Joker can be sent to battle each another. The Dude is in&nbsp;<cite>The Matrix</cite>.</p>\n\n<p>But I prefer to be optimistic. I choose hope. I see Etewaf as the Balrog, the helter-skelter, the A-pop-alypse that rains cleansing fire down onto the otaku landscape, burns away the chaff, and forces us to start over with only a few thin, near-meatless scraps on which to build.</p>\n\n<p>In order to save pop culture future, we&rsquo;ve got to make the present pop culture suck, at least for a little while.</p>\n\n<p>How do we do this? How do we bring back that sweet longing for more that spawned Gears of War, the Crank films, and the entire Joss Whedon oeuvre? Simple: We&rsquo;ve got to speed up the process. We&rsquo;ve got to stoke the volcano. We&rsquo;ve got to catalog, collate, and cross-pollinate. We must bring about Etewaf, and soon.</p>\n\n<p>It has already started. It&rsquo;s all around us. VH1 list shows.<cite>Freddy vs. Jason</cite>. Websites that list the 10 biggest sports meltdowns, the 50 weirdest plastic surgeries, the 200 harshest nut shots.&nbsp;<cite>Alien vs. Predator</cite>. Lists of fails, lists of boobs, lists of deleted movie scenes. Entire TV seasons on iTunes. An entire studio&rsquo;s film vault, downloadable with a click. Easter egg scenes of wild sex in&nbsp;<cite>Grand Theft Auto</cite>. Hell,&nbsp;<cite>Grand Theft Auto</cite>, period. And yes, I know that a lot of what I&rsquo;m listing here seems like it&rsquo;s outside of the &ldquo;nerd world&rdquo; and part of the wider pop culture. Well, I&rsquo;ve got news for you&mdash;pop culture&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">is</span>&nbsp;nerd culture. The fans of&nbsp;<cite>Real Housewives of Hoboken</cite>&nbsp;watch, discuss, and absorb their show the same way a geek watched&nbsp;<cite>Dark Shadows</cite>&nbsp;or obsessed over his eighth-level half-elf ranger character in Dungeons &amp; Dragons. It&rsquo;s the method of consumption, not what&rsquo;s on the plate.</p>\n\n<p>Since there&rsquo;s no going back&mdash;no reverse on the out-of-control locomotive we&rsquo;ve created&mdash;we&rsquo;ve got to dump nitro into the engines. We need to get serious, and I&rsquo;m here to outline my own personal fantasy: We start with lists of the best lists of boobs. Every Beatles song, along with every alternate take, along with every cover version of every one of their songs and every alternate take of every cover version, all on your chewing-gum-sized iPod nano. Goonies vs. Saw. Every book on your Kindle. Every book&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">on</span>&nbsp;Kindle on every Kindle.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/05/25/the-human-centipede-gets-the-video-game-tribute-it-deserves/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\"><cite>The Human Centipede</cite></a>&nbsp;done with the cast of<cite>The Hills</cite>&nbsp;and directed by the Coen brothers.</p>\n\n<p>That&rsquo;s when we&rsquo;ll reach Etewaf singularity. Pop culture will become self-aware. It will happen in the&nbsp;<cite>A.V. Club</cite>&nbsp;first: A brilliant Nathan Rabin column about the worst Turkish rip-offs of American comic book characters will suddenly begin writing its own comments, each a single sentence from the sequel to&nbsp;<cite>A Confederacy of Dunces</cite>. Then a fourth and fifth season of&nbsp;<cite>Arrested Development</cite>, directed by David Milch of<cite>Deadwood</cite>, will appear suddenly in the TV Shows section of iTunes. Someone BitTorrenting a&nbsp;<cite>Crass</cite>&nbsp;bootleg will suddenly find their hard drive crammed with Elvis Presley&rsquo;s &ldquo;lost&rdquo; grunge album from 1994. And everyone&rsquo;s TiVo will record&nbsp;<cite>Ghostbusters III</cite>, starring Peter Sellers, Lee Marvin, and John Candy.</p>\n\n<p>This will last only a moment. We&rsquo;ll have one minute before pop culture swells and blackens like a rotten peach and then explodes, sending every movie, album, book, and TV show flying away into space. Maybe tendrils and fragments of them will attach to asteroids or plop down on ice planets light-years away. A billion years after our sun burns out, a race of intelligent ice crystals will build a culture based on dialog from&nbsp;<cite>The Princess Bride</cite>. On another planet, intelligent gas clouds will wait for the yearly passing of the &ldquo;Lebowski&rdquo; comet. One of the rings of Saturn will be made from blurbs for the softcover release of&nbsp;<cite>Infinite Jest</cite>, twirled forever into a ribbon of effusive praise.</p>\n\n<p>But back here on Earth, we&rsquo;ll enter year zero for pop culture. All that we&rsquo;ll have left to work with will be a VHS copy of<cite><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zapped!\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Zapped</a>!</cite>, the soundtrack to&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0082694/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">The Road Warrior</a></cite>, and Steve Ditko&rsquo;s eight-issue run on&nbsp;<cite><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shade,_the_Changing_Man\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">Shade: The Changing Man</a></cite>. For a while&mdash;maybe a generation&mdash;pop culture pastimes will revolve around politics and farming.</p>\n\n<p>But the same way a farmer has to endure a few fallow seasons after he&rsquo;s overplanted, a new, richer loam will begin to appear in the wake of our tilling. From&nbsp;<cite>Zapped!</cite>&nbsp;will arise a telekinesis epic from James Cameron. Paul Thomas Anderson will do a smaller, single-character study of a man who can move matchbooks with his mind and how he uses this skill to pursue a casino waitress. Then the Coen brothers will veer off, doing a movie about pyrokenesis set in 1980s Cleveland, while out of Japan will come a subgenre of telekinetic horror featuring pale, whispering children. And we&rsquo;ll build from there&mdash;precognition, telepathy, and, most radically, normal people falling in love and dealing with jobs and life. Maybe also car crashes.</p>\n\n<p><cite>The Road Warrior</cite>&nbsp;soundtrack, all Wagnerian strings and military snare drums, will germinate into a driving, gut-bucket subgenre called waste-rock. And, as a counterpoint, flute-driven folk. Then there&rsquo;ll be the inevitable remixes, mashups, and pirated-only releases. A new Beatles will arise, only they&rsquo;ll be Iranian.</p>\n\n<p><cite>Shade: The Changing Man</cite>&nbsp;will become the new&nbsp;<cite>Catcher in the Rye</cite>. Ditko&rsquo;s thin-fingered art will appear on lunch boxes, T-shirts, and magazine covers. Someone will write an even thinner, sparser, simpler version called&nbsp;<cite>Shade</cite>. Someone else will write a 1,000-page meditation about Shade&rsquo;s home planet. Eventually, someone will try to kill the Iranian John Lennon with a hat, based on one panel from issue 3. A whole generation of authors under 20 will have their love&mdash;or disgust&mdash;of these comics to thank for their careers.</p>\n\n<p>So the topsoil we&rsquo;re coated in needs to wash away for a while. I want my daughter to have a 1987 the way I did and experience the otaku thrill. While everyone else is grooving on the latest Jay-Z,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lesclaypool.com/diesel/\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 3px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(180, 231, 248); outline: 0px; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; -webkit-transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); transition: background 0.15s cubic-bezier(0.33, 0.66, 0.66, 1); color: inherit; text-decoration: none; box-shadow: rgb(180, 231, 248) 0px -5px 0px inset;\">5 Gallons of Diesel</a>, I&rsquo;d like her to share a secret look with a friend, both of them hip to the fact that, from Germany, there&rsquo;s a bootleg MP3 of a group called Dr. Cali-gory, pioneers of superviolent line-dancing music. And I want her to enjoy that secret look for a little while before Dr. Cali-gory&rsquo;s songs get used in commercials for cruise lines.</p>\n\n<p>Etewaf now!</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">Patton Oswalt</span>&nbsp;(@pattonoswalt)&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">is a comedian, actor, and author. His first book,</span>&nbsp;Zombie Spaceship Wasteland (Scribner)<span style=\"font-family:exchange ssm 4i,exchange ssm 4r,georgia,serif\">, comes out in January.</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-02 16:37:04',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (29,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'Intel president steps down amid management shifts','img/contents/1834731507cd3fe3553123b28eb60573.jpg','img/contents/2586810b10f0bdd8bbf996d83bf1a9aa.jpg','Renee James, president of Intel Corporation, delivers the keynote speech at the opening of Computex 2014 in Taipei, Taiwan. (Wally Santana, AP)',NULL,'<p>NEW YORK &mdash; Major changes are coming to Intel&rsquo;s top management. In a message to employees, CEO Brian Krzanich said Intel president Renee James would be stepping down to pursue &ldquo;an external CEO role,&rdquo; though she&rsquo;ll stick around until January to help with the transition.</p>\n\n<p>Intel also announced the retirement of Arvind Sodhani, the president of Intel Capital, and a 35-year veteran of the company. His replacement is Intel&rsquo;s President of Mergers and Acquisitions Wendell Brooks, who will assume an expanded role.</p>\n\n<p>Other high-ranking Intel executives are also leaving the company, with other top managers taking on expanded responsibilities. The company&nbsp;indicated that these and other organizational shifts are being made to streamline operations and better position Intel for growth.</p>\n\n<p>&ldquo;We are aligning our leadership structure to continue to become more efficient in order to deliver the benefits of our strategy even faster than before,&rdquo; Krzanich said in a statement.</p>\n\n<p>Intel supplies chips for more than 80% of the personal computer market but has been wounded of late by declining PC sales. Krzanich is looking to expand beyond Intel&rsquo;s core businesses by providing chips for smart cars and so-called Internet of Things appliances. That was a major strategic motivator behind Intel&rsquo;s purchase last month of Altera, in an all-cash transaction valued at a whopping $16.7 billion.</p>\n\n<p>Intel&rsquo;s stock price is up 2.39%&nbsp;in &nbsp;trading Thursday morning.</p>\n\n<p>Email:&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:ebaig@usatoday.co\" style=\"border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 164, 59);\">ebaig@usatoday.c</a>om;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://twitter.com/edbaig\" style=\"border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 164, 59);\">Follow @edbaig on Twitter</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Source</strong></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://americasmarkets.usatoday.com/2015/07/02/intel-president-steps-down-amid-management-shifts/\">http://americasmarkets.usatoday.com/2015/07/02/intel-president-steps-down-amid-management-shifts/</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-02 15:37:03',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (35,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'New  Google Glass may be in testing','img/contents/608712f0d2b3fa9e88af3c9e6ebbabcc.png','img/contents/df1bac6c7800c839bd6c13e644827486.jpg','At the beginning of this year, the Google Glass program was moved into Tony Fadell\'s Nest division and the questions surrounding the wearable changed from \"when will this weird head gadget finally die\" to \"when will this weird head gadget be reinvented and released to consumers.\" Since then, Eric Schmidt insisted that the program is far from dead and the CEO of Italian eyewear Luxxotica told the Wall Street Journal said a \"second version\" that incorporated the \"second thoughts\" Google had about the platform was coming \"soon.\"','0','<p>Now,&nbsp;<em>Droid Life</em>&nbsp;has dug up a&nbsp;submission to the FCC&nbsp;that shows fairly compelling evidence that Google is actively testing the next version of Glass. These kinds FCC documents used to be a rich source for people looking to learn about what gadgets were coming soon, but in recent years both those companies and the FCC have learned to lock up actual product photos under confidentiality agreements. Nevertheless, there are still details to be found amongst the tests, which require companies to disclose whether or not the radios inside these gadgets are safe for use around humans. Thus, we know that the device with the FCC ID&nbsp;A4R-GG1 supports various Wi-Fi bands and Bluetooth.</p>\n\n<p><q>GLASS IS COMING BACK</q></p>\n\n<p>But more interestingly, these documents also require that companies disclose where the FCC label will appear and what it will look like. And in this case, Google is taking advantage of the&nbsp;2014 E-Label act, which lets companies bury those labels away in the settings instead of printing them on the device itself. So instead of speculating about the shape of the device based on the size and position of a sticker, we get to speculate on the software of the device. Here, the GG1&#39;s documentation also gives us details: it&#39;s going to appear on a particularly Glass-like rectangular display and it&#39;s available on a submenu that requires users to &quot;scroll left and right&quot; &mdash; the scrolling directions used on the last version of Glass.</p>\n\n<p>Does all that add up to solid proof that the GG1 is the next version of Glass and that it will be coming out in 2015? Let&#39;s say it adds up to a solid &quot;maybe,&quot; since FCC documents rarely provide anything that definitive. But it certainly seems like Google is intent on taking another swing at convincing consumers they will want a computer on their face.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Source:&nbsp;http://www.theverge.com/2015/7/3/8889271/gg1-new-google-glass-fcc-tests</p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-03 14:37:18',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (44,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'Maybe You Won\'t Get Windows 10 on July 29th','img/contents/2984a2a87968c1bbee235c225883412f.png','img/contents/a10264303c652fddf9cf3a61d6785f29.jpg','Officially, Windows 10 is coming July 29th, but not everyone will get it that day now, says Microsoft, it will roll out in waves','0','<p><span style=\"color:rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family:georgia,serif; font-size:15px\">The official Windows Blog&nbsp;</span><a href=\"http://blogs.windows.com/bloggingwindows/2015/07/02/windows-10-preparing-to-upgrade-one-billion-devices/\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; color: rgb(40, 173, 230); line-height: 24px; text-decoration: none; font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 15px;\" target=\"_blank\">explains:</a></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>Starting on July 29, we will start rolling out Windows 10 to our Windows Insiders. From there, we will start notifying reserved systems in waves, slowly scaling up after July 29th. Each day of the roll-out, we will listen, learn and update the experience for all Windows 10 users.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>So if you&rsquo;re part of Microsoft&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://insider.windows.com/\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; color: rgb(40, 173, 230); line-height: inherit; text-decoration: none;\" target=\"_blank\">Windows Insider beta testing program</a>,&nbsp;<em>maybe</em>&nbsp;you&rsquo;ll get it on July 29th. Maybe. For everyone else, you&rsquo;d better have clicked&nbsp;<a href=\"http://gizmodo.com/why-yes-that-creepy-icon-is-your-free-copy-of-window-1708121347\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; color: rgb(40, 173, 230); line-height: inherit; text-decoration: none;\">that &ldquo;Get Windows 10&rdquo; prompt that mysteriously showed up in your Windows toolbar</a>&nbsp;to reserve your digital copy of the OS, because those will also be rolling out in waves. Microsoft doesn&rsquo;t say if they&rsquo;re first-come, first-serve, but the company doesn&rsquo;t say they&nbsp;<em>aren&rsquo;t</em>, either.</p>\n\n<p>Honestly, this is probably a good thing. From what I&rsquo;ve seen of the preview builds, Windows 10 isn&rsquo;t quite ready. I&rsquo;ve run into a wide variety of bugs that you don&rsquo;t typically see this close to the launch of a major operating system. Tom Warren, a Windows 10 expert at&nbsp;<em>The Verge</em>, seems to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theverge.com/2015/6/2/8704191/is-windows-10-ready\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; color: rgb(40, 173, 230); line-height: inherit; text-decoration: none;\" target=\"_blank\">agree</a>. Launching this way lets Microsoft iron out these issues slowly, relying on its most dedicated and enthusiastic users to help spot the bugs&mdash;instead of facing a potential backlash by releasing a &ldquo;finished&rdquo; OS to everyone simultaneously.</p>\n\n<p>And it&rsquo;s hard to argue with that strategy when Microsoft is handing out Windows 10 for free!</p>\n\n<p>Just don&rsquo;t be surprised if&mdash;when July 29th rolls around&mdash;you can&rsquo;t find your copy.</p>\n\n<p>Source:&nbsp;http://gizmodo.com/okay-so-maybe-you-wont-get-windows-10-on-july-29th-1715532559</p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-03 15:37:02',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (45,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'What Apple is doing differently #AppleMusic','img/contents/3e33db6cbf9867bdc9adc08c867465cf.png','img/contents/501cb526fbf4b2386b9d395ffac6b87d.png','Apple Music has three main features that set it apart from rival services.\n','0','<h3><span style=\"font-size:13px\">One is Beats 1, a 24-hour live radio station. The other major streaming music services stick with what&#39;s known as asynchronous, tailored radio -- that is, the hip-hop station you play on Pandora will be different than the hip-hop station I&#39;m listening to at the same time. Beats 1 will play the same music, with the same DJ commentary and curation, at the same time for everyone worldwide.</span></h3>\n\n<p>Apple Music differs from rivals by having a live worldwide radio station, a platform for artists to interact with fans and the ability to control the experience with voice commands.</p>\n\n<p>The second is Connect. The section lets artists share lyrics, backstage photos, songs and videos directly with fans and get their feedback. Musicians and fans can interact -- listeners can comment and artists can respond, plus anything posted is shareable on Messages, Facebook, Twitter and email. Though other subscription services let artists use the platforms to reach fans, Connect is the most elaborate and dedicated platform so far.</p>\n\n<p>The last is Siri integration. It&#39;s more consumer-focused than Connect, which holds the most appeal for artists as a way to reach fans, and it&#39;s more engaging than Beats 1, which is designed to be something you can play and just lean back to hear for a while.</p>\n\n<p>Music voice commands aren&#39;t unique to Apple Music. Google Now, the voice recognition element to Google&#39;s&nbsp;Android&nbsp;mobile operating system, allows users to perform simple commands like playing the specific song or pausing a track, but won&#39;t respond to more conversational requests like &quot;play the song from the movie &#39;Boyhood.&#39;&quot;</p>\n\n<p>Amazon introduced its voice-activated, Internet-connected wireless speaker Echo last year, and it is shipping the device to consumers widely starting next month. It can play specific songs from the Prime Music service that is part of Amazon&#39;s $99-a-year membership program, and it will spin up stations you&#39;ve created on Pandora or iHeart Radio if you link an account.</p>\n\n<p>But Siri&#39;s range of commands appear to be more sophisticated. And Echo stays in your home, while Siri follows you on your smartphone. That&#39;s a key point since streaming music services routinely report that most of their listening is on mobile devices.</p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-03 06:37:23',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (46,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'#BlackBerry #Android #AT&T???','img/contents/ffd00bf0b24ced97b3e61ca20a97af11.jpg','img/contents/a424269a15a4e00a49fde8154e07523e.png','We\'ve expected for a month or so that BlackBerry is working on an Android phone with a \"dual curved display\" that slides up to reveal a physical keyboard underneath. It is supposedly based on a device that was originally announced at Mobile World Congress back in March, and back then the best image we had to go off of was a low-resolution snapshot of the device being held up on stage. Now, Evan Blass (aka @evleaks) has posted a high-resolution render of the device, codenamed Venice, to Twitter.',NULL,'<p>It reveals the aforementioned display, curved at the sides like the&nbsp;Samsung&nbsp;Galaxy S6 Edge. There&#39;s a speaker at the bottom, and if you look closely at the last photo you can see that the basic design mostly matches up. It looks as though BlackBerry has chosen to excise dedicated Send and End keys &mdash; presumably because the device is now going to run Android instead of BlackBerry 10. It also seem possible that there&#39;s still a keyboard scurried away underneath that screen. The one other notable thing about Blass&#39; image is that it has Google app icons strewn about &mdash; which should mean that it has full access to&nbsp;Google&#39;s&nbsp;suite of apps and services. Blass also claims that the&nbsp;Venice will be coming to AT&amp;T.</p>\n\n<p>Last month,&nbsp;Reuters originally reported&nbsp;that BlackBerry would make the switch to Android. If this render proves accurate (and Blass has a long history of posting accurate leaks), it might well be coming soon. It&#39;s been a very long time since there&#39;s been a decent Android device with a physical keyboard and an even longer time since there&#39;s been a vertical sliding phone with a physical keyboard. If BlackBerry pulls this off and actually releases something good, a lot of&nbsp;old Palm Pre fans&nbsp;are going to be pretty happy.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Source:&nbsp;http://www.theverge.com/2015/7/3/8889621/blackberry-venice-android-phone-att</p>\n','g-ocanto','0','2015-07-03 08:37:30',NULL,NULL,NULL),
  (51,'1','3','Blog',NULL,'Know the #New #GoPro Hero 4 Session [Video]','img/contents/022dd78f8c8b90fc06032252d7dc3689.jpg','img/contents/2ac73c5a12e6d9317f89c1eb38015812.jpg','Strapped to my hand was GoPro’s new camera: the $399 Hero 4 Session, available next week. It’s cube-shaped and measures less than 1.5 inches long on every side. It shoots 1440p video at 30 frames per second, 1080p up to 60 frames per second, and 720p up to 100 frames per second. It’s waterproof up to 10 meters so it doesn’t require a bulky housing, which made it the perfect camera to stick on the hand that I was using on top of my paddle. It got the shot.','0','<p>The Session is extremely simple to use: you start and stop it with just one press of a button. In fact, the Session only has two buttons. The main one is a red, circular button found on the top side of the camera. Tap it, and the Session turns on and starts recording. Tap it again to stop recording, and the Session turns off. YOU OPERATE THE SESSION WITH ONE BUTTON, AND IT HELPS SAVE BATTERY This helps with battery life &mdash; a problem GoPro has long battled with its cameras. The Session&rsquo;s internal battery should last between one to two hours running consistently, but turning it on and off each time stretches the battery life much further. When I started the hour-and-a-half rafting trip, the Session had two-thirds of its battery life remaining, and by the end, it had outlasted a fully charged Hero 4 Black and Hero+ LCD. A 3-second press-and-hold on the main button will trigger a time-lapse photo mode. If you want to shoot single or burst photos, however, you have to change to these modes in the GoPro app. The only other button on the Session is for turning the camera&rsquo;s Wi-Fi on and off.</p>\n\n<div class=\"m-feature__body\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 21px;\">\n<div class=\"m-photo-essay\" id=\"gallery8663426\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; clear: both;\">\n<p style=\"text-align:right\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<div>\n<p>In fact, to change any settings on the Session, you have to use GoPro&rsquo;s app or the included Wi-Fi remote. That&rsquo;s probably for the best, considering there are only two buttons and just one tiny screen on the camera. But GoPro has improved the ease of its on-camera menu system over the years, so if you&rsquo;ve gotten used to changing your settings on the fly, it could take some time to acclimate to the Session.</p>\n<iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/pzMRr5eTtho\" width=\"560\"></iframe>\n\n<p>One of the biggest benefits of the Session&rsquo;s small size is how much harder it is to notice, no matter where you mount it. GoPro has also slimmed down its cameras over the years &mdash; the Hero 4 Black and Silver, in particular, are very light and small &mdash; but when you snap them into a housing and mount them to a helmet or to your wrist, you definitely still feel them when you&rsquo;re moving around.</p>\n\n<p>THE HERO 4 SESSION IS WATERPROOF OUT OF THE BOX</p>\n\n<p>The Session, on the other hand, is waterproof out of the box. It does use a small skeleton case (much like the&nbsp;frame mount&nbsp;the company sells for its bigger Hero cameras, but cubed) in order to attach it to the various mounts. I mounted it to my hand during our rafting trip and could barely feel it as we sped down the river. A bigger Hero 4 stuck inside a waterproof housing would have been much more cumbersome.</p>\n\n<p>Ditching the need for a housing also solves another long-standing problem with GoPro&#39;s cameras: the audio. The Session has two microphones &mdash; one on the front, and one on the back &mdash; and it dynamically switches between them to reduces wind noise. They never get muffled, and they&#39;re built to drain liquid fast, so the audio even sounds good when the camera comes out from underwater.</p>\n\n<p>As small as it looks on its own, when you place a Session next to a naked Hero 4 Black or Silver, they don&rsquo;t look that much different. Put them in their various mounts and cases, though, and you can&rsquo;t help but notice how much space the Session saves you.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none\">\n <li><img alt=\"\" class=\"lazy-loaded vox-lazy-load\" src=\"https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-TyN7o130L9ypmITADe__C0fhIk=/1020x0/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3847354/gopro-hero-4-session-03055.0.png\" style=\"border:0px; box-sizing:border-box; display:block; height:auto; margin:0px auto; max-width:100%; width:1023px\" title=\"\" /></li>\n  <li><img alt=\"\" class=\"lazy-loaded vox-lazy-load\" src=\"https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/1hYjQYZMazT3sMiMeAL7vroaNYo=/1020x0/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3847356/gopro-hero-4-session-03057.0.png\" style=\"border:0px; box-sizing:border-box; display:block; height:auto; margin:0px auto; max-width:100%; width:1023px\" title=\"\" /></li>\n  <li><img alt=\"\" class=\"lazy-loaded vox-lazy-load\" src=\"https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/7W57rf2327-TwlqUGzw9G-bwe5c=/1020x0/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3847364/gopro-hero-4-session-03064.0.png\" style=\"border:0px; box-sizing:border-box; display:block; height:auto; margin:0px auto; max-width:100%; width:1023px\" title=\"\" /></li>\n  <li><img alt=\"\" class=\"lazy-loaded vox-lazy-load\" src=\"https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/URWi5rIdxRXfVr2qQl5Ri4klYyE=/1020x0/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3847390/gopro-hero-4-session-7827.0.png\" style=\"border:0px; box-sizing:border-box; display:block; height:auto; margin:0px auto; max-width:100%; width:1023px\" title=\"\" /></li>\n <li><img alt=\"\" class=\"lazy-loaded vox-lazy-load\" src=\"https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Ogtf_HFHwJ-lUY1yjPuKrd7CQoY=/1020x0/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3847394/gopro-hero-4-session-7772.0.png\" style=\"border:0px; box-sizing:bor